YouTube Trending Videos Data Analysis¶

This project aims to analyze datasets containing daily trending YouTube videos. The dataset includes data from Great Britain, USA, Canada, Germany, France, South Korea, Russia, India, Mexico, and Japan. YouTube compiles a list of top trending videos, and this dataset covers several months of such trending YouTube videos.

The list is determined based on factors such as comments, views, and likes on the videos over time to identify the most popular ones. Videos are ranked according to criteria including comments, likes, the number of views, and the number of times they have been shared in order to showcase the top trending videos.

Data Types Conversions:

The first step in data cleaning involves correcting the data types of all the columns to enhance their manipulability and ease of maintenance. It should be noted that, for several columns, the data type was changed to strings. When the data types are displayed, they appear as objects because strings are a type of object in pandas.

Data cleaning includes the following steps:

  • Splitting the values in the 'trending_date' column into separate columns for date, month, and year.
  • Updating the values in the year column.
  • Removing the 'trending_date' column and creating a new column using the date, month, and year columns.
  • Converting the data type of the 'trending_date' into datetime format.
  • Converting the data types of all the other columns that require conversion.
  • Converting the data type of the 'publish_time' column into datetime format

The loop is used to apply changes on all the dataframe in all_dataframes list.

In [ ]:
for df in all_dataframes:
    # video_id
    df['video_id'] = df['video_id'].astype('str')

    # trending date
    # converting into string
    df['trending_date'] = df['trending_date'].astype('str')

    # splitting the trending_date value to seperate month, date, and year
    # The split() method splits a string into a list by specifying the separator
    date_pieces = (df['trending_date'].str.split('.'))

   # now saving each value in seperate column
    df['Year'] = date_pieces.str[0].astype(int)
    df['Day'] = date_pieces.str[1].astype(int)
    df['Month'] = date_pieces.str[2].astype(int)

    # the loop below is used to update the year column
    updatedyear = []
    for i in range(len(df)) :
        y = df.loc[i, "Year"]
        newy = y+2000
        updatedyear.append(newy)

    for i in range(len(df)):
        newy = updatedyear[i]
        tr = df.loc[i, "Year"]
        df['Year'].replace(to_replace = tr, value = newy, inplace=True)

    del df['trending_date']
    df['trending_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df[['Year', 'Month', 'Day']], format = "%Y-%m-%d")
    del df['Year']
    del df['Day']
    del df['Month']

    #title
    df['title'] = df['title'].astype('str')
    #channel_title
    df['channel_title'] = df['channel_title'].astype('str')
    #category_id
    df['category_id'] = df['category_id'].astype(str)

    #tags
    df['tags'] = df['tags'].astype('str')

    # views, likes, dislikes, comment_count are already in correct data types i.e int64

    #thumbnail_link
    df['thumbnail_link'] = df['thumbnail_link'].astype('str')

    #description
    df['description'] = df['description'].astype('str')

    # Changing comments_disabled, ratings_disabled, video_error_or_removed from bool to categorical
    df['comments_disabled'] = df['comments_disabled'].astype('category')
    df['ratings_disabled'] = df['ratings_disabled'].astype('category')
    df['video_error_or_removed'] = df['video_error_or_removed'].astype('category')

    # publish_time
    df['publish_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['publish_time'], errors='coerce', format='%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%fZ')
  • Separating ‘publish_time’ into ‘publish_date’ and ‘publish_time’
  • Changing data type for 'publish_date' from object to 'datetime64[ns]'
In [ ]:

Handling missing values:¶

Handling missing values is essential as they can diminish the statistical power of the dataset and introduce bias, potentially resulting in invalid conclusions. Missing data can be addressed by calculating either the mean or median of the dataset and replacing the missing values accordingly.

The isnull() method is employed to check and manage NULL values in a data frame.

We have utilized a heatmap to visualize the data. Heatmaps display numeric tabular data, with cell colors indicating the values they contain. In the plots below, small orange blocks represent missing values, while black blocks represent non-null values. As observed, none of the datasets contain any missing values that would necessitate handling."

In [ ]:
for df in all_dataframes:

# Making copy of original dataframe
backup_df = combined_df.reset_index().sort_values('trending_date', ascending=False).set_index('video_id')

Next, we made the decision to enhance the quality of our data by sorting the entries within the dataset based on the 'trending_date.' This action was taken to ensure that the most recent trending videos would appear at the top of the dataset. We implemented this sorting process to focus on the current trends of the videos in each country, as they are more relevant to our project. We repeated this operation for each of the individual dataframes within the list we had previously created.

In [ ]:
# Sorting according to latest trending date while removing duplicates
combined_df = combined_df.reset_index().sort_values('trending_date', ascending=False).drop_duplicates('video_id',keep='first').set_index('video_id')
for df in all_dataframes:
    df = df.reset_index().sort_values('trending_date', ascending=False).set_index('video_id')

Inserting Category Column¶

reading randomly one json file to get insights from it's contents.

with open('US_category_id.json', 'r') as f:
    data = f.read()

obj = json.loads(data)

We randomly selected JSON files, all of which contain similar data. Each JSON file contains IDs ranging from 1 to 44, inclusive. Alongside each ID, there is information related to its category, title, kind, and more. Consequently, we can choose any one of the JSON files to map the category to the category ID in our data frame. We have successfully mapped the category IDs into the combined data frame. Furthermore, we have performed the same insertion process for all the individual data frames.

In [ ]:
category_id = {}
with open('DE_category_id.json', 'r') as f:
    d = json.load(f)
    for category in d['items']:
        category_id[category['id']] = category['snippet']['title']
combined_df.insert(2, 'category', combined_df['category_id'].map(category_id))
backup_df.insert(2, 'category', backup_df['category_id'].map(category_id))
for df in all_dataframes:
    df.insert(2, 'category', df['category_id'].map(category_id))

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

  • What is the likes-to-dislikes ratio in various categories?

  • Which video category receives the most likes?

  • Which videos are currently trending as the top five in each country?

  • Is the video with the most likes also the most trending?

  • Which category receives the most comments from users?

The like-dislike ratio in various categories¶

We began our analysis by examining the ratio of likes to dislikes for a popular video in each category. A higher ratio indicates that users found the video's content more enjoyable. As depicted in the screenshot below, the results are as follows:

In [ ]:
# calculating total likes for each category
likesdf=combined_df.groupby('category')['likes'].agg('sum')

# calculating total dislikes for each category
dislikesdf = combined_df.groupby('category')['dislikes'].agg('sum')

# calculating ratios of likes to dislikes
ratiodf = likesdf/dislikesdf

# most liked category to appear on top
ratiodf = ratiodf.sort_values(ascending=False).reset_index()
In [ ]:
# plotting bar chart
ratiodf.columns = ['category','ratio']
plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.barplot(x="ratio", y="category", data=ratiodf,
            label="Ratio of likes-dislikes in different categories")
Out[ ]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fe0c64e71d0>

Among the trending categories, it is evident that videos in the 'Pets and Animals' category have the highest ratio of likes to dislikes, whereas 'News' and 'Politics' videos have the lowest. From this, we can deduce that people are less divided on entertainment-centered videos compared to divisive topics like 'News,' which often leads to a split in user opinions.

Correlation between views, comments, likes, and dislikes¶

Next, we decided to determine whether there was any correlation between views, likes, dislikes, and comments.

In [ ]:

                  views  comment_count     likes  dislikes

When calculating the correlation among all the variables, we also consider the correlation of each feature with itself, which is always 1. This explains why the graph consistently displays a red diagonal line from the upper left to the lower right.

The data reveal that views and likes, likes and comment count, as well as dislikes and comment count, all exhibit a positive relationship. We reached this conclusion because a positive relationship exists whenever the correlation coefficient, denoted as 'corr,' is greater than zero.

In [ ]:
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df, y, test_size=0.2)

In both the train and test data, we used likes and dislikes as the independent variables (x-axis) to observe their impact on views.

In [ ]:
predictors = ["likes","dislikes"]
x_train = x_train[predictors]
x_test = x_test[predictors]

Linear regression¶

We used linear model, a built-in function for linear regression. LinearRegression() is used to train the model using our training data, and x test is used to predict test views using the likes in the test data.

In [ ]:
lm = linear_model.LinearRegression()
model = lm.fit(x_train, y_train)
predictions = model.predict(x_test)
# To retrieve the intercept
print(lm.intercept_)
# For retrieving the slope
print('regressor coffecient:',lm.coef_)
